const a = [
	{"id":4679,"text":"A 50-year-old man presents to the emergency room with severe abdominal pain referred to the upper back and left shoulder along with nausea and vomiting. Pain is not relieved by nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs). He has a long history of alcohol abuse. The physician is suspecting acute pancreatitis. Which of the following findings is most likely to be present in the patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 115.","responses":[{"text":"Raised serum gastrin levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raised serum amylase levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcifications on ultrasound abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stool for occult blood positive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raised serum transaminases","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4760,"text":"Which of the following nerves supplies the dermatome that is involved in referring the pain from the appendix to the umbilical region?","explanation":null,"reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 48.","responses":[{"text":"5th cranial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4th thoracic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd cervical nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10th thoracic nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"7th thoracic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4812,"text":"Which of the following drugs is recommended for the quickest treatment for ulcers?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw Hill; 2018: 1093.\r\n\r\n2) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 543, 544.","responses":[{"text":"H2 antagonists","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omeprazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Antacid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Misoprostol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5411,"text":"A 48-year-old female patient is brought to the emergency department with complaints of severe epigastric pain for 1 day, which became generalized and more severe for 3 hours. The pain is associated with vomiting, and she cannot tolerate even a liquid diet. She has a history of NSAID use for osteoarthritis for a long time. Her pulse is 120 beats/min, her blood pressure (BP) is 100/60 mmHg, she is afebrile, and her respiratory rate is 32 breaths/min. She has a tense tender abdomen with board-like rigidity. Gut sounds are inaudible. What is the most likely diagnosis in this patient?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis in this patient is **perforated peptic ulcer**. The clinical picture of the patient, including sudden severe pain, **history of NSAID use**, vomiting, inability to tolerate oral intake, and especially the physical examination findings of a rigid, \"board-like\" abdomen with absent gut sounds, suggests a **perforation of the gastrointestinal tract leading to peritonitis**. Peptic ulcers, especially in the setting of prolonged NSAID use, can perforate, leading to the leakage of gastric or duodenal contents into the peritoneal cavity. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Perforated gallbladder** typically presents with right upper quadrant pain and not generalized abdominal pain with board-like rigidity. \r\n\r\nWhile the patient does likely have an underlying peptic ulcer (given her history of NSAID use), the acute presentation with the rigidity of the abdomen is more consistent with a perforated peptic ulcer rather than just a peptic ulcer.\r\n\r\n**Acute cholecystitis** usually presents with right upper quadrant pain that may radiate to the right shoulder, often triggered by a fatty meal.\r\n\r\n**Acute pancreatitis** condition can cause severe epigastric pain radiating to the back and may be associated with nausea and vomiting. The abdomen is usually tender but not rigid like in perforation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 766, 767.","responses":[{"text":"Peptic ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated gallbladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated peptic ulcer","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5432,"text":"A 9-month-old female baby weighing 8 kg is brought to the emergency department with the complaint of loose motions for the last 3 days. On examination, the baby is irritable and her eyes are sunken. She is eager to drink and her skin pinch goes back slowly. What is the most likely diagnosis according to the IMNCI protocol?","explanation":null,"reference":"Diarrhoea and Dehydration. World Health Organization; 2008. Accessed July 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK143745/","responses":[{"text":"Shock","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mild dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Some dehydration","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5600,"text":"Energy expenditure necessary to maintain basic physiologic function under standardized condition(s) is called:","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 897.","responses":[{"text":"Optimum metabolic rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Energy equilibrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basal metabolic rate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Body mass index","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thermogenic effect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5618,"text":"A 32-year-old male patient, with a known case of Crohn’s disease, came to the outpatient department (OPD) with complaints of multiple discharging sinuses in the perianal region. What would be the most appropriate radiological investigation to reach the diagnosis in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 774.","responses":[{"text":"X-ray abdomen supine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computed tomography scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"WBC labelled scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnetic resonance imaging scan","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray abdomen erect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5619,"text":"A 35-year-old lady presented to the outpatient department (OPD) with intermittent diarrhea, fever, and on and off abdominal pain. Biopsy of this patient shows deep ulcers, marked lymphoid reaction, fibrosis, serositis, granuloma mass, and fistulas. Which of the following is the most likely possibility?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 797, table 17-9.","responses":[{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal polyposis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Malabsorption syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colorectal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5647,"text":"A 23-year-old male is brought to the emergency department with the complaint of pain in right lower abdomen for 5 days, which increases after eating. He has off and on diarrhea, with a history of weight loss for 3 months. He is also having intermittent fever for a few weeks. His pulse is 110 b/min, blood pressure (BP) is 100/70 mmHg and temperature is 100F. On examination, there is a tender palpable mass in the right iliac fossa absent bowel sounds. He also has two discharging fistulas in the peri-anal region. A complete blood picture was performed which depicts hemoglobin (Hb) of 8 gm/dl. What is the most likely cause of his condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 799.","responses":[{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn’s disease","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5650,"text":"A 34-year-old man presents in the gastrointestinal (GI) clinic with abdominal pain, and jaundice. His laboratory investigation confirms that he is positive for hepatitis C infection. Which of the following is true of hepatitis C infection?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 834.","responses":[{"text":"Alpha-interferon is an effective treatment to cure the infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection is common in women","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis C virus is a DNA virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Persistent infection and chronic hepatitis are the hall marks of the infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Commonly transmitted by sexual contact","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5654,"text":"Which of the following infection is associated with nasopharyngeal carcinoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 360.","responses":[{"text":"Human papillomavirus (HPV) infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoebic infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Helicobacter pylori infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Candidal infection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5660,"text":"A 50-year-old male with a history of ischemic heart disease presents with blood in the vomitus. There is no history of NSAIDs or steroid use. On examination, there is splenomegaly, ascites, and caput medusa around the umbilicus. Considering the diagnosis, what will be the best treatment option?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 304.","responses":[{"text":"I/V proton pump inhibitors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fluid resuscitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Terlipressin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral proton pump inhibitors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Octreotide","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5662,"text":"A 13-year-old child with a history of type 1 diabetes mellitus presents with intermittent diarrhea, abdominal pain, and vomiting. On examination, he has short stature with anemia, angular stomatitis, and paresthesia. What is the likely clinical diagnosis?","explanation":"**Celiac disease**, also known as gluten-sensitive enteropathy, is an **autoimmune condition** where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine. Clinical features can include chronic diarrhea, abdominal pain, vomiting, short stature due to malabsorption, anemia, and other signs of nutrient deficiencies like angular stomatitis. The coexistence of type-1 diabetes mellitus and celiac disease is also well-recognized, as both conditions have an autoimmune etiology. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS)** can cause abdominal pain and altered bowel habits, but it would not explain the anemia, short stature, or other specific symptoms mentioned.\r\n\r\n**Diabetic neuropathy** results from long-term high blood sugar levels and primarily affects the nerves, causing symptoms like numbness and pain. However, it would not account for the gastrointestinal symptoms or the anemia and angular stomatitis described.\r\n\r\n**Hypopituitarism** refers to decreased secretion of one or more of the pituitary hormones, leading to various symptoms depending on the hormone(s) affected. While it could cause growth issues, it would not typically present with the gastrointestinal symptoms mentioned.\r\n\r\n**Chronic giardiasis** is a parasitic infection that can cause diarrhea and abdominal pain, but it would not typically lead to the full spectrum of symptoms like angular stomatitis or the strong association with type-1 diabetes mellitus.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 783.","responses":[{"text":"Hypopituitarism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetic neuropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irritable bowel syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic giardiasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5664,"text":"A 44-year-old man, an emergency medical technician, has felt fatigued for the past 4 months. On physical examination, there are no remarkable findings. Laboratory studies show his alanine transaminase (ALT) 132 U/L and aspartate transaminase (AST) 113 U/L with total bilirubin 1.3 mg/dL and direct bilirubin 0.8 mg/dL. A liver biopsy is performed, and microscopic examination shows focal necrosis, interface inflammation with the extension of inflammation into the lobules from the triads. There is a ground-glass appearance of hepatocytes. Which of the following laboratory test findings is most characteristic for his disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 836, 837.","responses":[{"text":"Positive hepatitis B surface antigen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive anti hepatitis B core antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive anti hepatitis B surface antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive HCV RNA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive delta antigen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5668,"text":"A 25-year-old male presents to the emergency with severe abdominal pain radiating to the back and left shoulder for 24 hours. He has a history of anorexia and vomiting for two days. What is the most likely diagnosis in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 887.","responses":[{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5669,"text":"A 26-year-old man suffered a heavy blow on the chin in boxing after which there was the escape of blood and cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) from the nose, and extravasation of blood in the orbit which manifested as a \"black eye\". Which type of fracture could have led to this?","explanation":"A **fracture through the anterior cranial fossa** can be associated with a blow to the chin or frontal region. The fracture typically extends through the ethmoid bone, and patients may present with a **\"raccoon eye\" or \"black eye\"** due to blood accumulation in the orbit. CSF rhinorrhea, or the leakage of CSF from the nose, can also occur due to damage to the cribriform plate.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nGutter fracture is a linear skull fracture that runs parallel to the major suture lines.\r\n\r\nFracture through the middle cranial fossa could potentially result in CSF otorrhea (leakage of CSF from the ear) and may damage the facial or auditory nerves.\r\n\r\nFracture through the posterior cranial fossa can be associated with CSF otorrhea but wouldn't typically cause a \"black eye\" or CSF rhinorrhea.\r\n\r\nHinge fracture occurs in the posterior aspect of the skull and is commonly associated with falls.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 242.","responses":[{"text":"Gutter fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture through the posterior cranial fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hinge fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture through the anterior cranial fossa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture through the middle cranial fossa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5689,"text":"A 26-year-old woman has had bloody, mucoid, low-volume diarrhea for the past six weeks. The stool frequency is five per day. She is afebrile, with no abdominal mass or tenderness. Stool examination reveals only mucous and blood with few leukocytes, no ova or parasites seen. Colonoscopy shows a friable, erythematous mucosa extending from the rectum to the middle of the descending colon. Rectal biopsy shows acute mucosal inflammation with cryptitis and crypt abscesses. Which of the following is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 800.","responses":[{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Shigellosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomembranous colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischemic colitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5692,"text":"A 28-year-old lady falls from a scooter and gets minor abrasions on the arm and forearm and bruising of the scalp. After reaching home, she has a quarrel with her husband, receives mild blows on the face, and later dies. Autopsy reveals 100 ml of blood beneath a fractured skull at the site of the bruise. What is the probable cause of death?","explanation":"**Epidural hematoma** typically results from a traumatic injury, often associated with a fracture of the temporal bone. This can lead to rupture of the **middle meningeal artery**, causing blood to accumulate between the dura mater and the inner table of the skull. The classic presentation may include a **brief loss of consciousness (lucid interval)** followed by a **rapid decline in neurological status**, which could result in death if not treated promptly.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSubarachnoid hemorrhage usually occurs due to the rupture of a cerebral aneurysm and would present with sudden, severe headache often described as the \"worst headache of my life.\"\r\n\r\nContusions refer to brain bruises and are more commonly seen in deceleration injuries. While contusions can be fatal, the presentation given does not fit the classic scenario of a contusion as the cause of death.\r\n\r\nSubdural hematoma results from the tearing of bridging veins between the dura and arachnoid. It typically presents with a more insidious onset and might not be the result of a mild blow or trauma.\r\n\r\nIntracerebral hemorrhage refers to bleeding within the brain parenchyma itself. It can be due to hypertension, vascular malformations, or other causes but does not align with the trauma and rapid decline in this patient.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 243.","responses":[{"text":"Subdural hematoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subarachnoid hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidural hematoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Contusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracerebral hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5693,"text":"A 30-year-old girl ingested an unknown substance and died. A post-mortem was carried out to find the cause of death. The oral cavity showed a diffuse grayish-white escharotic appearance. Also, the gastrointestinal (GI) tract was inflamed but the cecum and large intestine showed intense inflammation along with gangrene. What do you think is the probable substance she ingested?","explanation":"**Mercury** poisoning can result in a range of symptoms, and one of its effects when ingested in large amounts is the development of an **escharotic or corrosive effect** on the gastrointestinal mucosa. The presentation of an escharotic appearance of the oral cavity and the severe inflammation and gangrenous changes, especially in the cecum and large intestine, are consistent with mercury ingestion.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nArsenic poisoning typically causes symptoms like vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and can cause QT interval prolongation on ECG. It does not typically cause the intense inflammation and gangrene as described.\r\n\r\nSilver ingestion or exposure can result in argyria, which is a blue-gray discoloration of the skin but does not cause the described gastrointestinal effects.\r\n\r\nLead poisoning can cause neurological symptoms, anemia, and abdominal pain, commonly referred to as \"lead colic,\" but it does not produce the described escharotic effects or the intense inflammation and gangrene in the cecum and large intestine.\r\n\r\nCopper poisoning can lead to hemolytic anemia, jaundice, and renal failure. It can cause gastrointestinal symptoms like vomiting and diarrhea but does not typically cause the described oral or gastrointestinal effects.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 496","responses":[{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mercury","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5695,"text":"A 30-year-old man got hit on the vertex of the head that led to a fracture of the base of the skull. However, on examination, the bruise was found on the mastoid process behind the ears. What could be the reason for these positive findings of bruises on the mastoid processes?","explanation":"The presence of bruises on the mastoid processes (behind the ears) in a patient with a head injury involving a skull fracture is likely due to **gravitational shifting of blood.** \r\n\r\nIn cases of head trauma, particularly with skull fractures, blood can accumulate beneath the scalp, and its movement is influenced by gravity. As a result, blood can flow or shift to dependent areas, leading to the appearance of bruising or swelling in locations like the mastoid processes. This phenomenon is often referred to as **\"Battle's sign\"** when it occurs behind the ears and is associated with basilar skull fractures. It is a clinical sign that can be indicative of a skull fracture and may prompt further evaluation and imaging.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 400.","responses":[{"text":"Gravitational shifting of blood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Color of skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Due to natural disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vascularity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Birth mark","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5696,"text":"A 30-year-old man met a road traffic accident, while he was riding a bike. The collision made his body drag on the road before he stopped by hitting a nearby tree. On examination, he was found to have superficial injuries involving only superficial layers of skin. What is the most probable injury he has sustained?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 233.","responses":[{"text":"Stabs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bruises","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lacerations","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contusions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abrasions","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5742,"text":"A 38-year-old man sitting on his terrace enjoying a cup of tea was suddenly hit on the head by a ricocheting glancing bullet that grazed his head and removed a part of the thickness of bone. What is this fracture called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 236.","responses":[{"text":"Communited fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gutter fracture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Depressed fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indented fracture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5745,"text":"A 40-year-old man who worked in the dye finishing industry for 20 years comes in with complaints of colic \u0026 bluish-black lines on the gums. Complete blood count along with peripheral smear shows anemia along with punctate basophilia in red blood cells. In the light of positive findings, what is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas, Gautam. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed., Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers, 2015: 501.","responses":[{"text":"Lead poisoning","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mercury poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thallium poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silver poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5749,"text":"A 43-year-old man complains of epigastric pain and nausea for 3 months. On physical examination, there are no abnormal findings. Upper GI endoscopy reveals a solitary sharply demarcated 2-cm shallow gastric ulcer at the antrum. Which of the following laboratory test findings is most relevant in this man?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 764.","responses":[{"text":"Positive anti-nuclear antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated serum gastrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive urea breath test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased plasma cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Achlorhydria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5782,"text":"A 50-year-old male presents with his investigations showing HBsAg positive, HBeAg negative, ALT 120 IU/ml, and HBV DNA \u003e10,000 IU/ml. His fibro scan shows an F3 score. What is the best option to start with?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 876.","responses":[{"text":"Lamivudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pegylated interferon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Telbuvidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entecavir","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adefovir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5785,"text":"A 55-year-old male presents to the emergency room with fever, chills \u0026 rigors. He has right hypochondrial pain and jaundice. What is the most appropriate diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 862.","responses":[{"text":"Liver abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholangitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pyelonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5786,"text":"A 60-year-old male with small bowel diverticulosis presents with steatorrhea. He undergoes certain investigations including a hydrogen breath test which is positive. Which of the following condition should be considered in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 808.","responses":[{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroenteritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tropical sprue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial overgrowth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic insufficiency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5839,"text":"What is the state of complete emaciation called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2020: 94.","responses":[{"text":"Chronic liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malabsorption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malnutrition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kwashiorkor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marasmus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5840,"text":"A young boy got hit during a fight by a baseball bat. It was a blunt injury with a perpendicular impact which resulted in a linear opening of the skin overlying the scalp. It resembled an incised wound. What is your most probable diagnosis of the type of injury he has sustained?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 195.","responses":[{"text":"Split laceration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal laceration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stretch laceration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Avulsion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5842,"text":"A young girl is attacked by thieves who badly injure her with knives. On examination, the wounds are present on her body and arm, clearly cut with no bruising at the wound edges. Gaping is also noted at the edges. In light of the above findings, what is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"**Incised wounds** are typically characterized by **clean-cut, sharp edges**. They are often caused by sharp objects like knives or glass, and they tend to have minimal tissue damage beyond the immediate area of the cut. \r\n\r\n\r\nLacerations are wounds characterized by irregular, torn, or jagged edges. They are typically caused by blunt trauma, like a blow or a fall, where the skin and underlying tissue are forcefully stretched and torn. This differs from the clean-cut appearance described in the scenario.\r\n\r\nStab wounds are usually the result of a sharp, pointed object penetrating the skin. They often have a central entry point with less pronounced gaping compared to incised wounds.\r\n\r\nA contusion is essentially a bruise. Bruises result from blunt trauma that damages blood vessels beneath the skin, causing blood to leak into the surrounding tissue. They do not involve sharp-edged cuts or incisions.\r\n\r\nBruises are caused by blunt trauma that damages blood vessels, leading to the discoloration of the skin. They do not involve clear-cut, sharp edges or gaping.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 233.","responses":[{"text":"Contusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Laceration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bruise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incised wound","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stab wound","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5844,"text":"Which of the following signs can help confirm appendicitis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Winterbottom, Christopher Toby. “Positive Psoas Sign in Presentation of Retroperitoneal Malignant Triton Tumour.” BMJ Case Reports, 5 Apr. 2010, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3047516/.","responses":[{"text":"Cullen’s sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Psoas sign","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Troisier’s sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trousseau sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Grey Turner’s sign","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5846,"text":"What is the most common site of diverticulitis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 803.","responses":[{"text":"Descending colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascending colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transverse colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sigmoid colon","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5850,"text":"A 29-year-old male presents to the outpatient department with a complaint of recurrent abdominal pain for the last 1 year, mostly in the lower abdomen that is relieved by defecation. He is also giving the history of increased frequency of stools approximately 3-4 times per day. He does not have weight loss \u0026 nighttime awakening due to these symptoms. On examination, he is vitally stable. Systemic and general physical examinations are unremarkable. Complete blood count and ESR are normal. What is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 796.","responses":[{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irritable bowel syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory bowel disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Giardiasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5853,"text":"A 3-week-old male is referred for persistent vomiting. He was well until 5 days ago but is now vomiting with each feed and is not putting on weight. After a test feed, he has projectile non-bilious vomiting. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2020: 557.","responses":[{"text":"Gastroesophageal reflux","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyloric stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5857,"text":"A 39-year-old female comes to the outpatient department with abdominal pain. She has a history of weight loss and jaundice. Labs reveal raised alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) and des-gamma-carboxyprothrombin (DCP) levels. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 873.\r\n\r\n2) Inagaki Y, Tang W, Makuuchi M, Hasegawa K, Sugawara Y, Kokudo N. Clinical and molecular insights into the hepatocellular carcinoma tumour marker des-γ-carboxyprothrombin. Liver International: Official Journal of the International Association for the Study of the Liver. Published January 2011. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20874725/","responses":[{"text":"Cholangiocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary hepatic lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver cirrhosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatocellular carcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5912,"text":"A female patient comes to the clinic with complaints of diarrhea along with fever and abdominal cramping. Colonoscopy revealed pseudomembrane formation on colonic mucosa. The patient has a history of long-term intake of antibiotics. She still complains of repeated episodes of colitis. The doctor recommends fecal bacterio-therapy. Which one of the following bacteria is most probably involved?","explanation":"***Clostridium difficile*** is a bacterium responsible for causing antibiotic-associated colitis, including the **pseudomembranous colitis** seen in the patient. It typically occurs after a person has been taking antibiotics, which can disrupt the normal balance of gut bacteria. This disruption allows *C. difficile* to overgrow and produce toxins that lead to the characteristic symptoms of diarrhea, abdominal cramping, and fever.\r\n\r\nFecal microbiota transplantation (fecal bacterio-therapy) can be used as a treatment for recurrent *C. difficile* infection. It involves transplanting fecal matter from a healthy donor into the patient's colon to restore the normal balance of gut bacteria and eliminate the *C. difficile* infection. This therapy can be highly effective in cases of recurrent or severe *C. difficile*-associated colitis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 791.","responses":[{"text":"Bacillus cereus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium perfringens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shigella dysenteriae","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5915,"text":"Gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) is associated with a mutation of?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 775, 776.","responses":[{"text":"PDGFR-A","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"WT-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"p-63","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PTEN","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"p-53","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5928,"text":"The process of collecting, compiling, and publishing demographic, economic, and social data pertaining to a specific time from all persons of a country is called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Gastrointestinal-II Module, Community Medicine, Topic: Demography-II.","responses":[{"text":"Surveillance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vital registration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Demographic sample survey","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Service statistics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population census","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5983,"text":"While examining a victim, the medicolegal officer writes a medicolegal certificate by mentioning a wound exposing bone without a fracture on the occipital area. How is this injury classified?","explanation":null,"reference":"Pakistan penal code. Accessed August 3, 2022. https://pljlawsite.com/html/ppc337a.htm","responses":[{"text":"Shajjah - I - Khafifah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Damigah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Ammah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Munaquillah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Mudihah","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5984,"text":"Which of the following represents the percentage of nitrogen that is retained in the body after absorption of diet?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hoffman JR, Falvo MJ. Protein – which is best? J Sports Sci Med. 2004;3(3):118-130. Accessed July 25, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3905294/","responses":[{"text":"Biological value of proteins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic pool of amino acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biological value of only essential amino acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total protein in the body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycemic index","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5993,"text":"Which of the following is used to treat a Helicobacter pylori infection?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw Hill; 2018: 1093.","responses":[{"text":"Clarithromycin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trimethoprim","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciprofloxacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythromycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penicillin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6098,"text":"Which of the following is a characteristic X-ray finding of jejunal obstruction?","explanation":null,"reference":"William NS, O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 27th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2018: 80, 1288.","responses":[{"text":"Air under diaphragm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Valvulae conniventes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"String of pearl appearance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stepladder sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thumbprinting sign","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8528,"text":"Which of these is closely related to the partially hydrogenated oils?","explanation":null,"reference":"Janapala US, Reddivari AKR. Low cholesterol diet. StatPearls. Published online May 8, 2022. Accessed August 23, 2022. https://www.statpearls.com/articlelibrary/viewarticle/24425/","responses":[{"text":"Cis form of fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mono unsaturated fats","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trans form of fat","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Poly unsaturated fats","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saturated fats","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9427,"text":"A hemodynamically unstable boy is brought to the emergency room with complaints of multiple fractured ribs on the left hypochondrium. Which of the following organs is most likely to be damaged?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, GIT-I, Introduction \u0026 divisions of GIT + abdominal quadrants \u0026 regions lecture slides, \"Contents of abdominal regions\"","responses":[{"text":"Head of pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Appendix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gall bladder","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10373,"text":"Which of the following is a side effect of ribavirin?","explanation":"**Hemolytic anemia** is a known side effect of ribavirin. **Ribavirin** is an antiviral medication used in the treatment of certain viral infections, including hepatitis C. One of its side effects is the potential to cause hemolytic anemia, a condition where red blood cells are destroyed faster than they can be produced, leading to a reduced red blood cell count. This can result in symptoms such as fatigue, pallor, and shortness of breath.","reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw Hill; 2018: 891.","responses":[{"text":"Constipation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutropenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diarrhea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10376,"text":"A 45-year-old man presents to the emergency room with wrist drop and foot drop. After evaluation, he is diagnosed with sideroblastic anemia. Which of the following enzymes is most likely to be affected in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Dow Lecture slides: GIT-2 module, Forensic Medicine slides, Topic: Lead and copper poisoning.\r\n\r\n(2) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 281.","responses":[{"text":"Protoporphyrinogen oxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dehydratase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ALA synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ALA dehydratase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chelatase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10377,"text":"A 7-year-old boy presents to the emergency room with complaints of abdominal pain in the umbilical region which transfers to the right lower quadrant. According to the parents, the pain started 6 hours ago and did not subside. On examination, rebound tenderness is observed. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated appendix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diverticulitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10378,"text":"A 38-year-old man presents to the emergency room with abdominal pain. On examination, the abdomen is soft and tender. An abdominal X-ray shows haustrations. Which part of the gut has haustrations?","explanation":null,"reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 317.","responses":[{"text":"Ileum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10379,"text":"On colonoscopy, a surgeon will differentiate the jejunum from ileum by which of the following?","explanation":"The following are the distinguishing features of jejunum and ileum:\r\n\r\nLength and thickness: The jejunum is typically located more proximally (closer to the stomach) than the ileum and is longer, about 2.5 meters. In contrast, the ileum is shorter, measuring approximately 3.6 meters. It is wider and **thicker than the ileum**.\r\n\r\n Vasa recta: The jejunum has **longer vasa recta** (straight arteries in the mesentery) compared to the ileum. The ileum has shorter vasa recta.\r\n\r\n Arterial arcades: The jejunum has **fewer arterial arcades**, while the ileum has more complex arterial arcades.\r\n\r\n Mesenteric fat: The jejunum typically has **less mesenteric fat**, making it appear redder and more vascular, while the ileum has more mesenteric fat, giving it a paler appearance.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 311.\r\n\r\n(2) Knipe H. Jejunum vs ileum | radiology reference article | radiopaedia. Org. Radiopaedia. https://radiopaedia.org/articles/jejunum-vs-ileum-1","responses":[{"text":"Jejunum has fewer arterial arcades","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum has shorter vasa recta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum has narrower lumen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum has more mesenteric fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum has thinner wall","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10380,"text":"A 2-month-old infant is brought from a rural area to the emergency room of a city hospital with fever, diarrhea, and vomiting. The stools are watery with frequent episodes. The child is given oral rehydration. The illness resolves without the administration of antibiotics. What is the most likely pathogen involved?","explanation":null,"reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 322, 323.","responses":[{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norwalk virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rotavirus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vibrio cholera","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10381,"text":"While circulating in the blood, copper largely binds to which of the following proteins?","explanation":"**Copper** largely binds to ceruloplasmin, which is a copper-transporting protein. **Ceruloplasmin** is the major copper-carrying protein in the blood and plays a crucial role in copper homeostasis. It also serves as an enzyme and an antioxidant, among other functions.\r\n---\r\n\r\nAlbumin: It primarily serves as a carrier for many substances, including hormones, fatty acids, and some drugs, but it is not the primary carrier for copper.\r\n\r\nTransferrin: Transferrin is a transport protein that mainly carries iron in the blood, not copper.\r\n\r\nHaptoglobin: Haptoglobin is another blood protein, but its primary role is to bind and remove free hemoglobin that is released into the bloodstream from red blood cells. It is not involved in copper transport.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 80.","responses":[{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ceruloplasmin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10382,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding split laceration?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 195.","responses":[{"text":"It can occur on the scrotal skin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It can occur on the forehead","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It occurs due to sudden compression between two hard objects","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a type of laceration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It looks like an incised wound","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10383,"text":"A 29-year-old man presents to the outpatient department with complaints of abdominal distension, flatulence, and occasional diarrhea. He is diagnosed with Entamoeba histolytica infection and subsequently given an oral drug which is bioactivated by reduction of its nitro group by ferredoxin, which is present in parasites. What is the drug most likely to be?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 605, 606. (2) Tinidazole - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed September 17, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutical-science/tinidazole.","responses":[{"text":"Pyrimethamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tinidazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diloxanide furoate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primaquine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloroquine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10384,"text":"A 29-year-old man presents to the outpatient department with complaints of abdominal distension, flatulence, and occasional diarrhea. He is diagnosed with Entamoeba histolytica infection. What is the treatment of choice?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, Ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th Ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 928.","responses":[{"text":"Iodoquinol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metronidazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diloxanide furoate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paromomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metronidazole and diloxanide furoate","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10387,"text":"Foods that have a low glycemic index are considered to be more beneficial because they cause less fluctuation in the secretion of a particular hormone. Which of the following is this hormone?","explanation":null,"reference":"Holesh JE, Aslam S, Martin A. Physiology, carbohydrates. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 14, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459280/","responses":[{"text":"Glucocorticoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroxine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10392,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding a stab wound?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 200, 201.","responses":[{"text":"Its greatest dimension is depth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It results from piercing with a pointed weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It may occur with a knife","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a wedge shaped opening wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In this injury bruising around the opening of the wound is seen","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10393,"text":"Blue-black lines in gum result from which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: GIT-2 module, Forensic Medicine slides, Topic: Lead and copper poisoning.","responses":[{"text":"Sulfate deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead sulphide deposition","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrous sulphide deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead nitrous sulphate deposition","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10394,"text":"In gluconeogenesis which enzyme is primarily present in the liver?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 121.","responses":[{"text":"Glucose dehydrogenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyruvate carboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose phosphatase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphofructokinase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10395,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding abrasion?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 189, 190.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a superficial wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It leads to permanent scar formation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Involves removal of superficial epithelial layer of the skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is caused by friction against a rough object","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10396,"text":"What is a wound defined as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 188.","responses":[{"text":"Penetration with long narrow, usually pointed, object that is deeper than its length and width","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A clean cut wound through the tissues, which is more long than deep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The extravasation of blood in the subcutaneous/subepithelial tissues due to rupture of blood vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Any injury with breach in natural continuity of skin or mucous membranes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The tearing or splitting of skin, mucous membranes, muscles or internal organs caused by either a shearing or a crushing force","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10397,"text":"What is a bruise defined as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 191.","responses":[{"text":"A clean cut wound through the tissues, which is more long than deep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The extravasation of blood in the subcutaneous/subepithelial tissues due to rupture of blood vessels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Any injury with breach in natural continuity of skin or mucous membranes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penetration with long narrow, usually pointed, object that is deeper than its length and width","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The tearing or splitting of skin, mucous membranes, muscles or internal organs caused by either a shearing or a crushing force","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10398,"text":"What is laceration defined as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 195.","responses":[{"text":"A clean cut wound through the tissues, which is more long than deep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penetration with long narrow, usually pointed, object that is deeper than its length and width","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The tearing or splitting of skin, mucous membranes, muscles or internal organs caused by either a shearing or a crushing force","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The extravasation of blood in the subcutaneous/subepithelial tissues due to rupture of blood vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Any injury with breach in natural continuity of skin or mucous membranes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10399,"text":"What is a stab wound defined as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 200.","responses":[{"text":"The tearing or splitting of skin, mucous membranes, muscles or internal organs caused by either a shearing or a crushing force","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The extravasation of blood in the subcutaneous/subepithelial tissues due to rupture of blood vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Any injury with breach in natural continuity of skin or mucous membranes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A clean cut wound through the tissues, which is more long than deep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penetration with long narrow, usually pointed, object that is deeper than its length and width","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10400,"text":"What is an incision wound defined as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 197.","responses":[{"text":"The tearing or splitting of skin, mucous membranes, muscles or internal organs caused by either a shearing or a crushing force","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penetration with long narrow, usually pointed, object that is deeper than its length and width","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The extravasation of blood in the subcutaneous/subepithelial tissues due to rupture of blood vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Any injury with breach in natural continuity of skin or mucous membranes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A clean cut wound through the tissues, which is more long than deep","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10401,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding age and color of a bruise?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 193.","responses":[{"text":"Blue on day 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Yellow on day 7-12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal at 1 week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Depends on size and swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Green on day 2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10402,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding hepatorenal syndrome?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: GIT-2 module, Medicine slides, Topic: Ascites and concept of SAAG.","responses":[{"text":"Diagnosed when serum creatinine \u003c 1.5 despite using diuretics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium avidity is the culprit","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1 develops more slowly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Laboratory finding consistent with post-renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dialysis is the mainstay treatment","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10415,"text":"Ascites resulting from an increase in hydrostatic pressure occurs in which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 462.","responses":[{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neoplasm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cirrhosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constrictive pericarditis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10429,"text":"A 5-day-old infant presented with diarrhea, vomiting, and abdominal pain. Which of the following enzyme deficiencies is likely to cause this?","explanation":null,"reference":"Malik TF, Panuganti KK. Lactose intolerance. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed September 18, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532285/","responses":[{"text":"Disaccharidase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hexokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethanol dehydrogenase (ADH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactate dehydrogenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucokinase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10434,"text":"Which of the following is not a risk factor for hepatitis-induced encephalopathy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 865.","responses":[{"text":"Dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paracentesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dietary proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperkalemia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10571,"text":"Which of the following drugs acts through cell surface receptors increasing the activity of Janus kinase (JAK)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: GIT-2 module, Pharmacology slides, Topic: Treatment of hepatitis.","responses":[{"text":"Telbivudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adefovir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interferon-alfa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lamivudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entecavir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10641,"text":"A 41-year-old patient presents to the emergency with hyperreflexia. On examination, his GCS score is 12/15. Which of the following is the correct grade of encephalopathy?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 857. (2) Grades of hepatic encephalopathy - west haven criteria ... GrepMed. Published July 10, 2020. Accessed September 18, 2022. https://grepmed.com/images/9233/hepatic-criteria-hepatology-grades-westhaven","responses":[{"text":"Grade I","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Grade IVB","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Grade III","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Grade IVA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Grade II","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10642,"text":"Which of the following is not a side effect of interferon-alfa?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw Hill; 2018: 885. (2) Dow Lecture slides: GIT-2 module, Pharmacology slides, Topic: Treatment of hepatitis.","responses":[{"text":"Fatigue and myalgia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flu-like symptoms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutropenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mental alertness","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Headache","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10643,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding the pharmacokinetics of interferon-alfa?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: GIT-2 module, Pharmacology slides, Topic: Treatment of hepatitis.","responses":[{"text":"Pegylated forms of IFN conjugated to polyethylene glycol can be administered once a week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conventional forms of IFN are usually administered daily or 3 times a week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absorption from intramuscular or subcutaneous injection is rapid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"There are several forms of IFN with minor differences in amino acid composition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elimination of IFN is mainly via proteolytic hydrolysis in the kidney","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10644,"text":"Which drug should be added to the regimen of hepatitis C virus in the addition of interferon-alfa?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: GIT-2 module, Pharmacology slides, Topic: Treatment of hepatitis.","responses":[{"text":"Lamivudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ranitidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribavirin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Entecavir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adefovir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10645,"text":"Which of the following represents the sex and age of a population?","explanation":"A **population pyramid** is a graphical representation of the distribution of various age groups in a population, which typically takes the shape of a pyramid when populations are growing. It is used to provide a clear picture of the age and sex distribution. The x-axis of the pyramid represents the number (or percentage) of people, while the y-axis represents age groups. Males are usually shown on the left and females on the right. Population pyramids can provide valuable insights into the demographic makeup of a country, including potential economic challenges or opportunities.","reference":"GIT and liver-II module; Community-medicine lecture slides; Topic: Population pyramid.","responses":[{"text":"Population growth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population dynamics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population pyramid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Population momentum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10646,"text":"What is a woman's physiological ability to bear and deliver children known as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ilyas M. Public Health and Community Medicine. 7th ed. Time Publishers; 2006: 91, 95-96.","responses":[{"text":"Total fertility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fertility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subfertility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Replacement level fertility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fecundity","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10647,"text":"Which of the following is defined as the number of births per thousand of the midyear population in a year?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: GIT-2 module, Community Medicine slides, Topic: Demography III.","responses":[{"text":"Age-specific birth rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total fertility rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"General fertility rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crude birth rate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fecundicity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10648,"text":"Which of the following is defined as the number of live births per thousand in an age group of a population?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture slides: GIT-2 module, Community Medicine slides, Topic: Demography III.","responses":[{"text":"Fecundicity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Age-specific birth rate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Total fertility rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crude birth rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"General fertility rate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10650,"text":"Which of the following nonfunctional plasma enzymes is elevated in alcoholics?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 882.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactate dehydrogenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acid phosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alkaline phosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gamma glutamyl transferase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10651,"text":"A 2-year-old child with fever for which mother gave her paracetamol every 4 hours. Later he presented with upper quadrant pain and jaundice. Which of the following is the likely cause?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 825.","responses":[{"text":"Viral hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmune hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute liver failure due to paracetamol poisoning","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatocellular carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10652,"text":"Transport of glucose across the basolateral membrane in intestinal cells occurs through which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hantzidiamantis PJ, Lappin SL. Physiology, glucose. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed September 18, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545201/","responses":[{"text":"Na+/glucose transporter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitated diffusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary active transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10653,"text":"Which of the following stimulates gastric acid secretion?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 814.","responses":[{"text":"Cholecystokinin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Motilin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10654,"text":"A 68-year-old patient presents with abdominal pain, jaundice, and a history of weight loss. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 116.","responses":[{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoma of the head of pancreas","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstruction of the main pancreatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoma of the tail and body of pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10655,"text":"A patient is diagnosed with acute pancreatitis. Which of the following laboratory findings will not be seen?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 837, 839.","responses":[{"text":"Elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated alanine aminotransferase (ALT)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated amylase and lipase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated hematocrit","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated glucose","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10656,"text":"A 31-year-old female presents to the emergency room with abdominal pain and diarrhea alternating with constipation. On stool analysis, a pale, foul-smelling stool is observed. She is advised to start a gluten-free diet. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 107.","responses":[{"text":"Celiac sprue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Whipple disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tropical sprue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10660,"text":"Which of the following is the appropriate emergency surgery recommended for a patient with severe ulcerative colitis?","explanation":null,"reference":"William NS, O’Connell PR, McCaskie AW, eds. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 27th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2018: 1270.","responses":[{"text":"Subtotal colectomy and end ileostomy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Proctocolectomy with ileal pouch-anal anastomosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporary loop ileostomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reserved proctocolectomy with ileal pouch-anal anastomosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proctocolectomy with end stage ileostomy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11409,"text":"A person presents to the emergency department with chronic diarrhea and abdominal pain for months. Findings show aphthous ulcers, deep linear fissures occupying the ascending and transverse colon but sparing the rectum and descending colon with skipped areas with excess fat creeping over mucosa. Cryptitis is also seen in lamina propria along with non-caseating granulomas. Which is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"The presentation includes chronic diarrhea and abdominal pain along with specific findings such as aphthous ulcers, deep linear fissures, and non-caseating granulomas in the lamina propria. These features are indicative of **Crohn's disease**. One of the hallmark characteristics of Crohn's is the presence of **\"skipped areas\"** of affected tissue, which contrasts with **ulcerative colitis** that usually shows continuous inflammation.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nLactose intolerance primarily causes diarrhea and bloating but does not lead to the aphthous ulcers, deep linear fissures, or non-caseating granulomas described in the question. Whipple disease is a systemic illness affecting multiple organs and is associated with a bacteria called *Tropheryma whipplei*; it would not specifically lead to the findings described.\r\n\r\nCeliac disease is an autoimmune disorder primarily affecting the small intestine in response to gluten intake and is characterized by villous atrophy rather than cryptitis and non-caseating granulomas.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 799.","responses":[{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactose intolerance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Whipple disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11943,"text":"What is the mechanism of action of cisapride that increases gastrointestinal motility and is used to treat GERD?","explanation":null,"reference":"Serotonin 5-ht4 receptor agonists. In: LiverTox: Clinical and Research Information on Drug-Induced Liver Injury. National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases; 2012. Accessed August 7, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK548948/","responses":[{"text":"Proton pump inhibitor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5-HT4 receptor agonist","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"5-HT4 receptor antagonist","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"D2 antagonist","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HT3 inhibitor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11944,"text":"Which of the following is a mechanism of action of sofosbuvir that is used in the treatment of the hepatitis C virus?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibits integrase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits fusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits DNA polymerase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits reverse transcriptase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits RNA polymerase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11945,"text":"Which of the following is the characteristic radiological hallmark of paralytic ileus?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 772.","responses":[{"text":"Valvulae conniventes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Double wall sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated loops","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumoperitoneum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rigler sign","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11946,"text":"Which of the following combinations of drugs is used for the treatment of HCV-genotype 1?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 440.","responses":[{"text":"Sofosbuvir + daclatasvir","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sofosbuvir + pibrentasvir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Daclatasvir + ledipasvir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Grazoprevir + Sofosbuvir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribavirin + velpatasvir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11947,"text":"Which of the following statements is true regarding the hepatitis C virus?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 874, 878.","responses":[{"text":"Its a DNA virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevention is via vaccines","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Results in chronic Infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transmitted via sexual contact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"More common in women","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11948,"text":"Which of the following antidiarrheal drugs can be given without a prescription?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sahi N, Nguyen R, Santos C. Loperamide. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed August 7, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557885/","responses":[{"text":"Loperamide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aluminum hydroxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bismuth subsalicylate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium hydroxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diphenoxylate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11959,"text":"Which of the following risk factors is most strongly associated with the development of fundic gland polyps?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 770.","responses":[{"text":"Familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"MEN-II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MEN-I","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CDKN2A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"TGF-beta","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11960,"text":"Which of the following imaging techniques is useful in the diagnosis of pancreatic carcinoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 895.","responses":[{"text":"Magnetic resonance imaging of abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computed tomography of abdomen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11961,"text":"Mutations of which of the following genes is not associated with the development of hereditary pancreatitis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 886.","responses":[{"text":"Homozygous CFTR mutation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heterozygous CFTR mutation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SPINK1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PRSS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SMAD4","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11962,"text":"Which of the following genes is involved in sporadic colon carcinoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 810.","responses":[{"text":"MLH3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MLH2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MLH1","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"MSH3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MSH1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11963,"text":"A 2-year-old child is brought to the emergency room with a history of loose stools for the past 3 days. On examination, the child is lethargic, has sunken eyes, and is unable to drink. What is the most appropriate treatment according to IMNCI?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2020: 183, 184.","responses":[{"text":"Oral rehydration solution 75 ml/Kg in hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Resomal 70 cc/Kg in 6 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous Ringer's lactate 100 mg/Kg in 3 hours","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral ciprofloxacin 20 mg/Kg/day for 5 days","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous ampicillin 100 mg/Kg/day for 5 days","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11964,"text":"Hepatic encephalopathy is a spectrum of disturbances in consciousness, ranging from subtle behavioral abnormalities to marked confusion and stupor, to deep coma and death. Which of the following is a useful indicator of its prognosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 826.","responses":[{"text":"Serum ammonia levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum creatinine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma sodium levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilirubin levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin time","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11965,"text":"Which of the following antiemetic drugs is effective in increasing gastric motility and is used in patients with diabetic gastroparesis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 547.","responses":[{"text":"Alprazolam","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoclopramide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lorazepam","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dolasetron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Droperidol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11966,"text":"Which of the following antibiotics is effective in patients with shigella dysentery?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 265.","responses":[{"text":"Metronidazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciprofloxacin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Norfloxacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloramphenicol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cephalosporin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11967,"text":"A 6-month-old boy presented to the clinic with a four hours history of\r\ncrying and intermittent drawing up of his knees to his chest and was looking very pale. He had passed several currant jelly stools. On abdominal examination, there was a sausage-like mass in the right upper quadrant. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2020: 560.","responses":[{"text":"Biliary atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hirschsprung disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malrotation of the gut","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intussusception","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Volvulus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11968,"text":"Which of the following drugs inhibits gastric acid secretion for about 18 hours?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 543.","responses":[{"text":"Femotidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omeprazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cimetidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoclopramide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ranitidine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11969,"text":"A 65-year-old male presented to the clinic with a complaint of blood in the vomitus and a history of significant weight loss with ulcer-like symptoms. On upper GI endoscopy, there was a mass in the stomach. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 771.","responses":[{"text":"Esophageal varices","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric adenocarcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric erosion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11970,"text":"A 35-year-old female patient presented to the outpatient department with a complaint of abdominal discomfort for 3 months that was relieved on defecation. She also gave a history of changes in bowel habits with vitals completely normal. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 796.","responses":[{"text":"Shigella infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholelithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemorrhoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irritable bowel syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11971,"text":"How do we diagnose irritable bowel syndrome?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 796.","responses":[{"text":"Colonoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum lipase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fecal calprotectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum amylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"On the basis of clinical criteria","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11977,"text":"Most of the potassium and sodium ions in the canaliculus of the parietal cells are reabsorbed into the cell cytoplasm, and another ion takes its place in the canaliculus. Which of the following ions is actively secreted in the canaliculus in exchange for potassium?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 812.","responses":[{"text":"Magnesium ion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrogen ion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydroxide ion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloride ion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicarbonate ion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11978,"text":"A 50-year-old truck driver presented to the outpatient department with the complaint of painful perianal swelling for a few months, which bursts on its own but recurs after some days and the wound never heals completely. On further investigation, he also gave a history of fever and pus discharge from the swelling. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 836.","responses":[{"text":"Perianal abscess","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemorrhoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anal fissure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectal ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11979,"text":"Which of the following is not a risk factor for cholangiocarcinoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 874.","responses":[{"text":"Fibropolycystic liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatolithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infestation by Clonorchis species","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary sclerosing cholangitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wilson disease","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11980,"text":"Which of the following is a cause of bleeding in subdural hematoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 245.","responses":[{"text":"Bridging and communicating veins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior cerebral artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diploic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle meningeal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior meningeal artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11991,"text":"A 45-year-old male patient presented to the outpatient department with the complaint of bloody diarrhea with stingy mucoid material for 1 year. He also gave a history of lower abdominal cramps that were temporarily relieved by defecation. What is the gold standard test for confirming this disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 800.\r\n\r\n(2) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 818.\r\n\r\n(3) Kaenkumchorn T, Wahbeh G. Ulcerative colitis: making the diagnosis. Gastroenterology Clinics of North America. Published December 2020. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33121687/","responses":[{"text":"Total blood count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileocolonoscopy and biopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnetic resonance imaging","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fecal calprotectin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12003,"text":"Which of the following organisms would cause diarrhea in a patient with pseudomembranous colitis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 104, 264.","responses":[{"text":"Echinoccus granulosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella typhi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entamoeba histolytica","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Campylobacter jejuni","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12004,"text":"What are the official counting of a population in the territory of a country and the collection of information on selected demographic and socioeconomic characteristics of the population called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Population Census - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/social-sciences/population-census#. Accessed 20 Aug. 2022.","responses":[{"text":"Surveillance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Statistics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Research","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population census","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Data collection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12005,"text":"A patient with a duodenal ulcer comes to the clinic with a complaint of blood in vomiting. The ulcer has eroded the posterior wall of the duodenum and ruptured which artery?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 105. (2) Gastroduodenal Artery - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/veterinary-science-and-veterinary-medicine/gastroduodenal-artery. Accessed 20 Aug. 2022.","responses":[{"text":"Left gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreaticoduodenal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle colic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroduodenal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12006,"text":"Which of the following arteries passes behind the first part of the duodenum?","explanation":null,"reference":"Gastroduodenal Artery - an Overview | ScienceDirect Topics. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/veterinary-science-and-veterinary-medicine/gastroduodenal-artery. Accessed 20 Aug. 2022.","responses":[{"text":"Left gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroduodenal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle colic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreaticoduodenal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12007,"text":"Which of the following drugs is effective in NSAID-induced peptic ulcers?","explanation":"**Misoprostol** is a synthetic prostaglandin E1 analogue that helps in the protection of the gastric mucosa from the ulcerogenic effects of NSAIDs. It promotes secretion of mucus and bicarbonate, increases mucosal blood flow, and stabilizes mucosal cells. This makes it effective in preventing and treating ulcers induced by NSAIDs.\r\n\r\nWhile metronidazole, bismuth subsalicylate, amoxicillin, and clarithromycin are used in combination or separately to treat ***Helicobacter pylori*** infections which can also cause peptic ulcers, they are not specifically used for NSAID-induced ulcers.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 163.","responses":[{"text":"Misoprostol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metronidazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bismuth subsalicylate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoxicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clarithromycin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12020,"text":"A case of a road accident is presented to the emergency department in which the windshield was broken and the front seat passenger received injuries on the face from broken glass pieces. Which of the following types of injuries best describes this condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 285.","responses":[{"text":"Fractures","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sparrow foot injury","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep cuts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Whiplash injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Countercop injury","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

export default a